 in Orne or Say in Indre, France, perhaps so called from a Gaulish personal name <i>Saius</i> + the Latin locative suffix <i>-acum</i> (see also French name 3 below).","English: nickname, perhaps for someone who made or sold say, a type of woollen cloth, or for an habitual wearer of clothes made of this material, from Middle English <i>sai(e)</i> ‘say’ (Old French <i>saie</i>, from Latin <i>saga</i>, plural of <i>sagum</i> ‘military cloak’). See also   Sayer  .","French (southern): topographic name from <i>saix</i> (from Latin <i>saxum</i>) ‘rock’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example, Say in Loire, Saix in Tarn and Vienne, Le Saix in Hautes-Alpes, or Les Saix in Isère."],"variants":[{"name":"Sey","meanings":["English and Scottish: probably a variant of   Say   particularly prevalent in Scotland.","Dutch and Flemish: from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigiheri</i> (see   Seger  ).","West African (Ghana): Akan (Fante) name of unexplained etymology."]},{"name":"Sayer","meanings":["English: common occupational name from Middle English <i>sayer</i>, a phonetic variant of   Sawyer  , which in Wales and neighboring English counties may have been reinforced by the synonymous Welsh <i>saer</i> ‘carpenter’ and everywhere by a possible borrowing into Middle English of Old French <i>seieor</i>, <i>saieur</i> ‘sawyer’.","English: rare occupational name perhaps denoting an assayer of metals, or a servant who tasted his lord's food before serving, from Middle English <i>saiour</i> ‘assayer, tester’ (a shortened form of Old French <i>assaiour</i>, ultimately from Late Latin <i>exagium</i>, a derivative of <i>exagmināre</i> ‘to weigh’).","English: rare occupational name for a professional reciter or minstrel, from Middle English <i>seier(e)</i> ‘speaker’."]},{"name":"Saye","meanings":["English: variant of   Say  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Saje</b>: nickname for someone with very dark, sooty hair, derived from the root of <i>sajast</i> ‘sooty’, or directly from <i>saja</i> ‘soot’.","West African (Liberia): from the personal name <i>Saye</i>, found among the Mano (Mah) people, denoting a first-born boy."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":39,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Say was born in 1343, in Wem, Shropshire, England. He married Elizabeth le Boteler 4th Baroness Boteler of Wem about 1381. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 27 July 1382, in Hertfordshire, England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1343–27 July 1382":"1343–27. juuli 1382","1345–1411":"1345–1411","1381–1478":"1381–1478","1343–1382":"1343–1382","abt. 1381/82":"umbes 1381","27 July 1382":"27. juuli 1382","1478":"1478","1411":"1411","1345":"1345","1343":"1343","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","Broxbourne, Hertfordshire, England":"Broxbourne, Hertfordshire, England","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1343–27 July 1382":"1343–27. heinäkuuta 1382","1345–1411":"1345–1411","1381–1478":"1381–1478","1343–1382":"1343–1382","abt. 1381/82":"noin 1381","27 July 1382":"27. heinäkuuta 1382","1478":"1478","1411":"1411","1345":"1345","1343"